samples.input: do female ferrets die if they don't mate

messages.content: do female ferrets die if they don't mate

Yes, female ferrets can suffer life-threatening complications if they don't mate. In fact, the condition, called aplastic anemia, is the result of sustained elevated estrogen levels when a female ferret (a jill) remains in estrus or is constantly in heat.  

As part of their unique reproductive cycle, female ferrets can remain in continuous estrus until they are mated. In heat, these ferrets can experience elevated estrogen levels, leading to bone marrow suppression, which, in turn, results in low levels of red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets - a hallmark problem of aplastic anemia that is fatal if left untreated.  

Preventative measures, including mating, spaying, and the use of hormone therapies, however, are available.
